    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.11.18_page_030_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "get along. The scar tissue of earlier interventions, British colonial and Indian, underlies their conflict. State borders imposed by the British jumbled tribal areas. The privileges some communities wrested from the central government—a jobs quota here, a land settlement there-enraged their neighbours. The conflict in Manipur was stirred by one such rivalry. The government in Delhi has sometimes intervened brutally. In 1966 India's then prime minister, Indira Gandhi, ordered air strikes on the city of Aizawl, in what is now Mizoram, to quell a secessionist uprising. Perhaps unsurprisingly, many north-easterners feel little allegiance to India; other Indians tend to look on them suspiciously.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6582160162206011,
          0.47844242327726244,
          0.9408396992493748,
          0.7034883722208141
        ],
        "order": 6
      }
    ]
  },
